	  <title>The Dot Product Operation: Exercises</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Evaluate the following dot products</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
					                <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{(2,-1)}{(6,1)}</latex>
                     </math>
				              </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>11</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
						                  <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{(2,-1)}{(6,1)} = 12 -1 =11</latex>
                        </math>
					                </para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{ (1,3,2) }{(-2,1,1)}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>3</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
						                  <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{(1,3,2)}{(-2,1,1)} = -2 +3 +2 = 3</latex>
                        </math>
					                </para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
					                <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{(-3,1,3,1)}{(6,1,1,1)}</latex>
                     </math>
				              </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>-13</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
						                  <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{(-3,1,3,1)}{(6,1,1,1)} = -18 + 1 + 3 + 1 = -13</latex>
                        </math>
					                </para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Each of the following expressions contains an invalid use of the dot product. Write out exactly what is wrong before looking at the solution.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{ (312,-781,2013) }{ (9143,691, -901,1618) } = 443</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The dot product is only defined for two vectors from the same space <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math>; i.e. both vectors must have the same number of coordinates. – In the case at hand the first vector has <math>
                           <latex>3</latex>
                        </math> coordinates, and the second has <math>
                           <latex>4</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore the dot product of these two vectors is not defined. The assertion that the dot product of these two vectors has the value 443 is entirely out of place, because the dot product of the given vectors isn’t equal to anything ... it is simply not defined.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{ (4,1,3) }{ (1, -2,1) } = (4, -2,3)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The dot product of two vectors always is a number (in this case: <math>
                           <latex>5</latex>
                        </math>), not a vector as is suggested here. Therefore the suggested identity is false.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\dfrac{(2,3,1)}{(2,3,1)} = 1</latex>
                     </math>
				              </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The division of one vector by another is not defined. An identity of the suggested form is, therefore, invalid.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
					                <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{ (\Vect{y}/ \Vect{x}) }{ \Vect{x} } = \Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math>
				              </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The problem here is the same as in the previous problem: The operation of dividing the vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math> by the vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> is not defined. No identity of the suggested form is valid.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Verify each of the identities below by evaluating the left and the right hand side separately.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\DotPr{ (2,5,-1) }{ \left((3,1,1) + (2,-3,4)\right) } = \DotPr{ (2,5,-1) }{ (3,1,1) } + \DotPr{ (2,5,-1) }{ (2,-3,4) }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
