	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Amongst the vectors given below, determine which pair(s) are perpendicular.</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>\Vect{a} = (1,3,-1), \quad \Vect{b} = (4,0,1), \quad \Vect{x} = (2,0,-8), \quad \Vect{y} = (4,1,7)</latex>
			         </math.display>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <answer.exercise>
            <answer.exercise.block>
               <answer.exercise.block.body>
				              <para>
                     <para.body>
					                   <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{b}</latex>
                        </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math>, and <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
                        </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math>. – None of the other pairs of vectors is perpendicular.</para.body>
                  </para>
			            </answer.exercise.block.body>
            </answer.exercise.block>
         </answer.exercise>
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>For each pair of vectors you need to evaluate the dot product. A pair of vectors is perpendicular if their dot product is <math>
                     <latex>0</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>This exercise may help you overcome a certain psychological hurdle: Whenever you want to know whether two vectors are perpendicular, try to show that their dot product is <math>
                     <latex>0</latex>
                  </math> – regardless of how ‘complicated’ the vectors may look at first sight. – Apply this method in the following situation</para.body>
            </para>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Assume that <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> are nonzero vectors in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[5]</latex>
                  </math>. Show that the vector</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>\Vect{z} := \Vect{y} - \dfrac{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} } } \cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
			         </math.display>
			         <para>
               <para.body>is perpendicular to <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math>
			            </para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>We evaluate the dot product of the given vectors</para.body>
               </para>
				
				           <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{\Vect{z}}{\Vect{x}}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \left( \Vect{y} - \dfrac{\DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{y}} }{ \DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{x}} } \cdot \Vect{x} \right) }{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex/>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=	</latex>
                        </math>
                        <companion>
                           <info>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use the distributivity law of the dot product</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </companion>
                        <companion>
                           <info>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use the distributivity law of the dot product</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </companion>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{\Vect{y}}{\Vect{x}}\ -\ \dfrac{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }{ \DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{x}} } \cdot ( \DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{x} })</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex/>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=	</latex>
                        </math>
                        <companion>
                           <info>
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Note that division and multiplication by the nonzero number <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{x} \bullet \Vect{x}</latex>
                                    </math> is allowed. In addition we use the commutativity law of the dot product: <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{y} \bullet \Vect{x} = \Vect{x} \bullet \Vect{y}</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                        <companion>
                           <info>
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Note that division and multiplication by the nonzero number <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{x} \bullet \Vect{x}</latex>
                                    </math> is allowed. In addition we use the commutativity law of the dot product: <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{y} \bullet \Vect{x} = \Vect{x} \bullet \Vect{y}</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{\Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } - \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex/>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>

				           <para>
                  <para.body>So <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	
